{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569319"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22099"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22099"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.04,0.02,0.06,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116465"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15060"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98464"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5899"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116465"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to a rural General Practice-run Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of severe right subcostal pain radiating to her back. The pain is constant, burning in nature, and unrelieved by paracetamol. She describes the pain as eight out of 10 in severity and notes mild nausea. She has a medical history of hypertriglyceridaemia, gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, and osteoarthritis. Her medications include atorvastatin, omeprazole, and glucosamine. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally, with her last binge drinking episode two weeks ago. She is a retired school teacher and has not travelled recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable and is guarding her right upper quadrant. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Four hours after presentation, examination reveals the following (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral valaciclovir","Intravenous ceftriaxone","Oral amoxicillin-clavulanate","Oral prednisolone","Urgent surgical referral"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe unilateral pain followed by the development of vesicular lesions in a dermatomal distribution, characteristic of herpes zoster (shingles). The prodromal pain typically precedes the rash by 24-72 hours, and the grouped vesicles on an erythematous base in a dermatomal pattern confirm the diagnosis. The slightly elevated inflammatory markers and mild transaminitis are consistent with the systemic inflammatory response to herpes zoster.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral valaciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Antiviral therapy should be initiated within 72 hours of rash onset to reduce the severity and duration of symptoms and potentially prevent post-herpetic neuralgia. Valaciclovir 1000mg three times daily for seven days is the standard treatment. In a rural setting, oral therapy is practical and effective for immunocompetent patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for severe bacterial infections such as ascending cholangitis or pyelonephritis. While the initial presentation with right upper quadrant pain and mild inflammatory marker elevation could suggest biliary pathology, the development of dermatomal vesicles clarifies the diagnosis as herpes zoster.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E would be used for mild to moderate bacterial infections including cholecystitis or cellulitis. The vesicular rash in a dermatomal distribution is pathognomonic for herpes zoster, which requires antiviral rather than antibacterial therapy. The mild elevation in inflammatory markers does not indicate bacterial superinfection at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E has been studied as an adjunct to antiviral therapy in herpes zoster, but evidence for its benefit is limited. It is not recommended as monotherapy and its use remains controversial. The priority is antiviral therapy, and corticosteroids alone would not address the viral replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E might have been considered given the initial presentation with right subcostal pain, mild fever, and elevated inflammatory markers suggesting possible cholecystitis or pancreatitis. However, the development of dermatomal vesicles clarifies the diagnosis as herpes zoster, which is managed medically rather than surgically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antiviral therapy, adequate analgesia is essential as severe pain is a hallmark of herpes zoster. This may require opioid analgesia in the acute phase. Early treatment is crucial to minimise complications, particularly post-herpetic neuralgia, which is more common in older patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early antiviral therapy within 72 hours of rash onset reduces the severity and duration of herpes zoster and may prevent post-herpetic neuralgia.","Herpes zoster pain typically precedes the characteristic vesicular rash by 24-72 hours, requiring clinical suspicion for diagnosis.","Adequate analgesia is essential in managing herpes zoster as severe pain is a hallmark feature and can persist as post-herpetic neuralgia."],"references":["Saguil A, Kane S, Mercado M, Lauters R. Herpes Zoster and Postherpetic Neuralgia: Prevention and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Nov 15;96(10):656-663."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98464"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22099"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15623"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15623"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e033355e-b290-4c1f-968f-17e8f4e1624c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e033355e-b290-4c1f-968f-17e8f4e1624c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98464"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15060"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116465"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology"